flowRoot.flowPara: If a blood alcohol test was not administered and was not a basis for serving this notice, you have a right to forthwith request a test to determine your blood alcohol level. In the event the test indicates that your blood alcohol level does not exceed 50 milligrams of alcohol in 100 milliliters of blood, the prohibition from driving is terminated. The prohibition will not appear on your driving record and you will be allowed to drive.

If a prescribed physical coordination test was not administered and was not the basis for serving this notice, you have a right to forthwith request that the peace officer submit you to a prescribed physical coordination test to determine whether or not your ability to drive is affected by a drug other than alcohol. In the event that the prescribed physical coordination test does not indicate that your ability to drive is affected by a drug, the prohibition from driving is terminated. The prohibition will not appear on your driving record and you will be allowed to drive.

You should be aware that if you drive a motor vehicle while prohibited, you are subject to a maximum 60-day impoundment of the vehicle you operate, and a charge of Driving While Prohibited, which carries a minimum $500 fine, possible imprisonment, and an automatic 12-month driving prohibition

If you were served with this Notice of 24-Hour Prohibition, you may, within 7 days of being served, apply to the superintendent of Motor Vehicles for a review of the prohibition. If you apply for a review, you must: (1) file an application with the Superintendent at a Driver Services Centre; and (2) pay the prescribed application fee. You may attach any written statement or other evidence that you wish the Superintendent to consider.

After you have applied for a review, the Superintendent will send you a copy of the peace officer’s report and allow you to make a further written submission. In a review, the prohibition can only be revoked if: (1) you had the right to request and the officer failed to administer a test of your blood alcohol level when you requested it (alcohol); (2) you had the right to request and the officer failed to administer the prescribed physical coordination test when you requested it (drugs); or, (3) you were not the driver. No other factors may be considered. If the prohibition is revoked on review, it will be removed from your driving record. All review application fees are non-refundable, regardless of the review outcome.

Under the Motor Vehicle Act drivers whose driving records meet criteria prescribed in the Motor Vehicle Act Regulations are required to complete remedial and ignition interlock programs. The criteria may include driving records of drivers with three or more 24-hour prohibitions within 5 years. Other prohibitions on your driving record combined with this prohibition may also meet the criteria. See RoadSafetyBC’s website for more information: www.gov.bc.ca/roadsafetybc Note: Mandatory remedial and ignition interlock program requirements are not subject to a reconsideration process. Ignition interlock program requirements may be subject to exemption if satisfactory evidence is provided that a chronic medical condition prevents you from participating.If your driving record does not meet the criteria, the Superintendent may still require you to participate in a remedial or ignition interlock program under section 25.1 of the Motor Vehicle Act if the Superintendent finds your driving record to be unsatisfactory. You may apply for a reconsideration.
